 aphrodisiacs were recommended for the treatment of infertility, and how men and women utilised them to regulate their fertility. Via themes such as gender, witchcraft and domestic medical practice, it shows that aphrodisiacs were more than just sexual curiosities - they were medicines which operated in a number of different ways unfamiliar now, and their use illuminates popular understandings of sex and reproduction in this period. Dr Jennifer Evans is a Lecturer in Early Modern History at the University of Hertfordshire.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aEarly Modern History. 4aHistory of Science & Medicine. 7aHISTORY / Renaissance.2bisacsh  aAphrodisiacs.  aScottish freedom.  aaphrodisiacs.  aaristocratic achievement.  adomestic medical practice.  aearly modern England.  afertility.  agender.  amedicine.  apolitical governance.  areproduction.  areproductive success.  aself-governance.  asexual desire.  asexuality.  awitchcraft.1 aEvans, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2014z978311143136940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978178204368340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782043683423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782043683/original  a978-3-11-143136-9  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2014b2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles